{
  "text": "Although at relatively coarse resolution, CMIP5 simulations can capture expected features of coastal SL variability. For example, [CITATION_1] explain some of the western boundary coastal SL change evident in most CMIP5 model projections via a theory which describes a balance between mass input to the western boundary due to Rossby waves from the ocean interior and equatorward mass ejection due to coastal-trapped wave propagation. There is, however, evidence that coastal SL projections are improved in higher resolution models (e.g., [CITATION_2] . For this reason, dynamical downscaling with regional climate models has been used to study the effects of climate change scenarios at the coast (e.g., [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Global climate models are, however, generally used for providing boundary conditions to the higher resolution regional climate models, and uncertainties in those conditions can still be a problem.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "52083900",
    "[CITATION_2]": "55206284",
    "[CITATION_3]": "128835605",
